        "excerpt": "You too have done evil, even more than your forefathers; for behold, you are each one walking according to the stubbornness of his own evil heart, without listening to Me.",
        "body": "The Q&A of verses 10-13 is a masterpiece of preemptive apologetics. God instructs Jeremiah to anticipate the objection before it is raised — and the objection is predictable precisely because it is the natural human defense under judgment: 'What did we do? Why us? What is our sin?' The question in verse 10 ('for what reason has the LORD declared all this great calamity?') is not the language of genuine inquiry; it is the rhetoric of the aggrieved, the language of people who have already decided they are victims.\n\nGod's answer runs in two stages. First, the forefathers (v. 11): they forsook Yahweh (azav — covenant rupture), followed other gods, served and bowed to them. The vocabulary is Deuteronomic (Deuteronomy 28-29; 31:16-17) — covenant-lawsuit language that the hearers would have recognized from Israel's founding documents. The forefathers broke the relationship that made them a people. But — and this is the chapter's critical move — the present generation cannot hide behind ancestral guilt. Verse 12 is emphatic: 'You too have done evil, even more than your forefathers.' The escalation is the indictment. Each one walks according to the sherirut lev ra (stubbornness of his own evil heart, without listening to Me). The evil is not systemic or structural in the sense of being externally imposed; it is the willful, individuated choice of each person. Jeremiah's anthropology here anticipates the new covenant diagnosis of 31:30-34 — the heart is the problem, and only a new heart will be the solution.\n\nThe consequence (v. 13) is exile into an unknown land — a land named only by its foreignness, contrasted implicitly with the known, named, given land of the fathers. In that land of exile, they will serve other gods 'day and night' — the bitter irony is that God fulfills their desire: they wanted other gods; He gives them a land full of them, with no competing witness to draw them back. Peter Davids's observation on the logic of divine judgment in Romans 1:24-28 ('God gave them over') applies directly here: the punishment is being given what you chose.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Azav* (forsake, v. 11) appears twice in the verse — once for the forefathers' action and once in God's restatement ('They abandoned Me') — the repeated verb emphasizes that this is not a theological abstraction but a personal abandonment. *Sherirut lev ra* (stubbornness of an evil heart, v. 12) is a Jeremianic signature phrase occurring at 3:17; 7:24; 9:14; 11:8; 13:10; 18:12 — it is Jeremiah's term for the root pathology beneath all Israel's covenant failures."
