        "excerpt": "For I will restore them to their own land which I gave to their fathers.",
        "body": "Verses 14-15 are among the most theologically daring statements in the prophetic literature. Israel's foundational creed — the Exodus oath, 'As the LORD lives who brought up the sons of Israel from the land of Egypt' — was the anchor of every psalm, every festival, and every legal appeal in the Old Testament. Deuteronomy repeats it. The Psalter celebrates it. The prophets invoke it as the paradigm of divine deliverance. Here God says: that oath will be replaced by a new oath. The future gathering from the north and from all the countries of dispersion will be so overwhelming, so definitively Yahweh's act, that the Exodus will recede into secondary status.\n\nThis is not the replacement of the old covenant by indifference to Israel — it is its surpassing by a greater act. The same God who kept the Exodus oath keeps this one; the same covenant faithfulness that delivered from Egypt delivers from Babylon and beyond. New Testament interpretation (Luke 9:31 uses 'exodus' — exodos — for the crucifixion; Revelation 15:3 sings 'the song of Moses and the Lamb') understands the greater-than-Exodus act as the cross and resurrection, the gathering of a new people from every nation. The Babylonian return of Ezra and Nehemiah was a partial fulfillment; the eschatological gathering remains the ultimate referent.\n\nVerses 16-18 then interrupt the restoration promise with a sober insertion: before restoration comes full accountability. The fishermen and hunters who pursue Israel from every mountain, hill, and rocky cleft are the instruments of divine judgment — the Babylonian armies functioning as God's conscripted agents. The divine omniscience of verse 17 ('My eyes are on all their ways') is the theological basis for the inescapability of judgment: there is no terrain and no concealment that places a person outside Yahweh's sight. Verse 18's 'double repayment' (*mishneh*) is not punitive excess but legal full-weight recompense — the language of Isaiah 40:2 ('she has received double for all her sins') where the same mishneh marks completed punishment as the precondition of comfort. The double payment clears the account before the restoration begins.\n\nReformed and classical Arminian interpreters agree on the structure: God's justice must be fully satisfied before His mercy is fully expressed. They disagree on the mechanism of individual appropriation, but not on the sequence. Jeremiah 16:14-18 makes the sequence canonical: judgment (vv. 16-18) precedes restoration (v. 15); the fishing and hunting come before the homecoming.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mishneh* (double, v. 18) — the word for the second-copy, the duplicate portion. In Deuteronomy 17:18 it is the king's 'copy' of the Torah; in Isaiah 40:2 and here it marks full equivalent payment. *Nachalah* (inheritance, v. 18) — Israel's land as God's own property held in trust; their desecration of it is therefore a violation of divine property rights, not merely cultural misconduct."
